    {
      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:hu35oubkccqrxl4ldgczpgw7/bafkreigzmdlxvcfs4icstv55yh27tbe77qkxyuyf6tiyb5h5trza3uzai4",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:hu35oubkccqrxl4ldgczpgw7/bafkreigzmdlxvcfs4icstv55yh27tbe77qkxyuyf6tiyb5h5trza3uzai4",
      "alt": "Hegel wrote that through its repetition a historical event asserts its necessity. When Napoleon lost in 1813 and was exiled to Elba, this defeat may have appeared as something contingent: with better military strategy he might have won. But when he returned to power again and lost at Waterloo, it became clear that his time is over, that his defeat was grounded in a deeper historical necessity. The same goes for Trump: his first victory could still be attributed to tactical mistakes, but now that he won again, it should become clear that Trumpian populism expresses a historical necessity.",
